        <p><font color="#333333" size="4" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif">Tuneful Unity at the Town Gate: Moving Towards Terestrial and Celestial Harmony in Sens&rsquo; <em>F&ecirc;te des Rameaux </em>Procession <br>
          <br>
Donna La Rue, Independent scholar</font></p>
      </div>
    <!-- InstanceEndEditable --><!-- InstanceBeginEditable name="Text" -->
      <p><font size="3" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif">The French archepiscoal town of Sens, a magnet for political and obediential emplantations, saw constant processions; Sens&rsquo; <em>Cath&eacute;dral de St. Etienne&rsquo;</em>s canons visited several local parishes on their festival days. One royal monastery, St.-Pierre-le-Vif, east of town, figured in archbishopric enthronements and, per 13th century manuscripts, Palm Sunday events. Gathering at the cathedral, people processed a mile to the (now destroyed) abbatial church where palms were blessed, returning for the cathedral&rsquo;s 10 AM <em>missa maiore</em>, chanting <em>Gloria, laus, et honor.<br>
            <br>
      </em>Sens MS6, a <em>typikon,</em> or liturgical guide, includes an extensive <em>consuetudinum</em> giving each Chapter official&rsquo;s job descriptions; fussy reminders to heat water for Maunday Thursday&rsquo;s footwashing; and prompts that the Archbishop must serve the canons a dram of spirits in his palace, yearly (only) at Easter. Sens MS6&rsquo;s instructions also, oddly, tell the <em>precentor</em> (choral director) to &ldquo;restart the (Palm Sunday) hymn as the people, (returning to the cathedral with consecrated palms) pass under the gate.&rdquo; Why? What gate?<br>
        <br>
      A large calfskin map; rubrics for <em>Domenica in Ramus</em> in a <em>processionale</em>, Sens MS7; and a <em>graduale,</em> MS16, clarify this. The choirboys ascended the <em>Portail de Notre Dame</em>&rsquo;s second story, singing as the crowd passed beneath them. Sound being slower than sight, restarting them caught the crowd up to the boys&rsquo; place in the hymn, once within hearing distance.<br>
        <br>
        Such pragmatic instructions for the use of civic spaces and sites exemplify Sens&rsquo; extraordinary liturgical imagination. Synchronized singing between the Senonais townsfolk and the <em>pueri,</em> perched like angels above them,created a hopeful earthly scene of cosmic harmony. Honoring the entrance with palms into the Holy City long ago, they enacted an aesthetic identification with Jesus, and the people of Jerusalem. Sens&rsquo; liturgists&rsquo; purely enjoyable performative moment was also fully symbolic of space, time and place.<br>
        <br>
      Briefly, heaven and earth were attuned </font></p>
